{{italictitle}} {{for|the television adaptation|Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas (TV program)}} [[File:EmmetOttersJugBandChristmas.jpg|thumb|First edition of ''Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas'']] '''''Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas''''' is a 1971 children's book written by [[Russell Hoban]] and illustrated by [[Lillian Hoban]]. It was adapted for a [[Muppets]] [[Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas|television special of the same name]] in 1977.
==Russell Hoban storybook== {{expand section|date=April 2013}} ''Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas'' was written by [[Russell Hoban]] and illustrated by his then-wife, [[Lillian Hoban]], in 1969. The book was published in 1971 by [[Parents' Magazine Press]]. The story tells of Emmet [[Otter]] and his Ma, a widow who scrapes by on the small amount of money she gets from doing laundry and that Emmet gets from doing odd jobs around their home in the town of Frogtown Hollow despite both of them often being cheated. Some of the people who cheated them are Old Lady [[Opossum|Possum]] and Gretchen [[Fox]] (the wife of [[Mayor]] Harrison Fox). As Christmas approaches, they hear of a talent contest in the nearby town of Waterville, and separately decide to enter to buy nice presents for each other—a nice guitar for Emmet, or a piano for Ma. However, in a twist on ''[[The Gift of the Magi]]'' by [[O. Henry]], they must sacrifice each other's livelihood for the talent contest. Ma [[pawnbroker|hocks]] Emmet's tools for dress fabric while Emmet turns Ma's washtub into a [[washtub bass]] for a [[jug band]].
==Jim Henson television special== {{main|Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas}}
==Jim Henson musical stage adaptation==
In 2008, [[the Jim Henson Company]] partnered with "iTheatrics" to develop a musical stage adaptation of the 1977 special. The musical featured a mix of stage actors, puppet characters and songs. [[Paul Williams (songwriter)|Paul Williams]] wrote new songs specifically for the stage show. [[Tim A. McDonald]] and [[Christopher Gattelli]] adapted the story for the stage, and Gattelli directed the production.<ref>[http://www.muppetnewsflash.com/2008/05/emmet-otter-stage-show-takes-shape.html "Emmet Otter" Stage Show Takes Shape] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603152303/http://www.muppetnewsflash.com/2008/05/emmet-otter-stage-show-takes-shape.html |date=2008-06-03 }}, May 27, 2008</ref> It premiered in a limited-run engagement on December 7, 2008 at the Goodspeed Opera House in [[East Haddam, Connecticut]], and closed on January 4, 2009. The cast featured Daniel Reichard (Emmet Otter), Cass Morgan (Ma Otter), Alan Campbell (Pa Otter), Kate Wetherhead (Jane), [[Lisa Howard (American actress)|Lisa Howard]] (Mrs. Gretchen Fox), and Jeff Hiller (Will Possum).<ref>Jones, Kenneth.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/124389.html "Emmet Otter Musical, with Reichard, Morgan, Campbell, Opens in CT"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220130051/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/124389.html |date=2008-12-20 }}, playbill.com, December 17, 2008</ref> The musical returned on December 5, 2009 and ran through January 3, 2010.
